## Business Structure & Legal

### Entity Structure Recommendation

**Recommendation: Single-Member LLC**

| Option | Pros | Cons |
|--------|------|------|
| **Sole Proprietorship** | Simple, no state fees | Personal liability exposure, less professional |
| **LLC** | Liability protection, tax flexibility, professional | Annual fees, slightly more paperwork |
| **S-Corp** | Tax savings at higher income | Complexity, payroll requirements |

**Why LLC:**
- Liability protection separates personal assets from business
- Pass-through taxation (no double taxation)
- Professional appearance for clients
- Required for some contracts/insurance
- Can elect S-Corp taxation later if beneficial

> Source: [SCORE](https://www.score.org/resource/blog-post/llcs-freelancers-understanding-liability-protection)

**Formation Steps:**
- [ ] File LLC with Wyoming (low fees, privacy, remote-friendly)
- [ ] Obtain EIN from IRS
- [ ] Create Operating Agreement
- [ ] Register for state business license (if required)
- [ ] Open business bank account

### Insurance Requirements

**Essential Coverage:**

| Coverage | Purpose | Estimated Cost |
|----------|---------|----------------|
| **Professional Liability (E&O)** | Protects against negligence claims, work errors | $61/mo (~$730/yr) |
| **General Liability** | Property damage, bodily injury | $42/mo (~$500/yr) |
| **Cyber Liability** | Data breaches, security incidents | $50-150/mo |
| **TOTAL** | | **$1,500-2,500/yr** |

> Sources: [Insureon](https://www.insureon.com/small-business-insurance/professional-liability/independent-contractors), [The Hartford](https://www.thehartford.com/professional-liability-insurance/sole-proprietorship)

**Why Professional Liability Matters:**
- Client contracts often require proof of E&O coverage
- Protects against claims of missed deadlines, undelivered services, negligence
- Single lawsuit without coverage can cost more than years of premiums
- Demonstrates professionalism to clients

**Important Note:** E&O coverage cannot be extended to subcontractors - they need their own coverage.

### Contract & Legal Documents

**Essential Documents:**

| Document | Purpose | When Used |
|----------|---------|-----------|
| **Master Services Agreement (MSA)** | Establishes ongoing relationship terms | Long-term clients |
| **Statement of Work (SOW)** | Project-specific deliverables, timeline, cost | Each project |
| **Proposal Template** | Win new business | Sales process |
| **Invoice Template** | Request payment | Monthly/milestone |
| **NDA (Mutual)** | Protect confidential information | Before discovery |
| **Independent Contractor Agreement** | For subcontractors | If hiring help |

**SOW Best Practices:**
Per [Consulting Success](https://www.consultingsuccess.com/consulting-statement-of-work-template):
- Be specific enough to prevent misunderstandings
- Include clear deliverables with acceptance criteria
- Note dependencies and assumptions
- Include change control process
- Separate from broader legal terms (use with MSA)

**Resources:**
- [Docracy](https://www.docracy.com/) - Free legal document templates
- [HelloSign](https://www.hellosign.com/) / DocuSign - Digital signatures
- [Bonsai](https://www.hellobonsai.com/) - Freelance contract templates

